  <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       PHASE 1 — YOU ARRIVE AT THE BEDSIDE
  ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="phase1">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Phase 1</span>
      <h2>You Arrive at the Bedside</h2>
    </div>

    <p class="phase-intro">
      You are the morning nurse on a medical-surgical unit. You receive handoff report and head to see your patient for the first time.
    </p>

    <div class="info-grid">
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>📋 Handoff Report</h3>
        <table class="data-table">
          <tbody>
            <tr><th>Patient</th><td>Bernadette Jackson</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Age / DOB</th><td>85 years old · May 10</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Gender / Race</th><td>Female · African American</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Admission Dx</th><td>Abdominal pain, UTI, urinary retention</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Allergy</th><td><span class="badge-danger">Penicillin</span></td></tr>
            <tr><th>Code Status</th><td>Full code</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>💊 Current Medications (on MAR)</h3>
        <ul class="med-list">
          <li>0.9% Normal Saline IV (rate per order)</li>
          <li>Levofloxacin 500 mg IV q12h</li>
          <li>Acetaminophen (dose per order)</li>
          <li>Digoxin (dose per order)</li>
          <li><span class="badge-warning">Oxybutynin</span> — started 1 week ago</li>
          <li><span class="badge-warning">Loratadine</span> — OTC, self-started 5 days ago</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="scene-box">
      <h3>🚪 Entering the Room — What You Observe</h3>
      <p>
        Mrs. Jackson is an 85-year-old woman lying in a hospital bed. She appears restless and somewhat confused, asking "Where am I? Where is my daughter?" Her speech is slightly slurred. The room is dimly lit. You notice the call light is on the far side of the bed, out of her reach.
      </p>
    </div>

    <h3>🔒 SWIPE Safety Assessment</h3>
    <p>Before touching the patient, perform your environmental safety check:</p>
    <table class="data-table">
      <thead><tr><th>Letter</th><th>Check</th><th>What You Find</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td><strong>S</strong></td><td>Siderails up</td><td>Only 1 rail up — <span class="text-danger">needs correction</span></td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>W</strong></td><td>Wristband on, matches chart</td><td>Present and correct</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>I</strong></td><td>IV lines — site, patency, rate, label</td><td>Right forearm, no redness; NS infusing</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>P</strong></td><td>Pull cord / call light within reach</td><td><span class="text-danger">Out of reach — needs correction</span></td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>E</strong></td><td>Equipment — bed position, socks, path clear</td><td>Bed elevated; no non-skid socks; path partly cluttered</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Clinical Reasoning: What safety corrections do you make immediately, and how do you introduce yourself to a confused patient?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>Immediate safety corrections:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Raise all appropriate siderails (2–3, per facility policy)</li>
          <li>Move call light within easy reach of Mrs. Jackson's hand</li>
          <li>Lower the bed to its lowest position</li>
          <li>Place non-skid socks on her feet</li>
          <li>Post a fall-risk sign on the door</li>
          <li>Clear any obstacles from the path to the bathroom</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Introduction to a confused patient — therapeutic communication:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Approach from the front, make eye contact, speak slowly and calmly</li>
          <li>"Hello, Mrs. Jackson. My name is ___, and I am your nurse today."</li>
          <li>Verify two identifiers: "Can you tell me your name and your date of birth?"</li>
          <li>Reorient gently: "You are in the hospital. You are safe. Your daughter has been notified."</li>
          <li>Use short, simple sentences — one idea at a time</li>
          <li>Explain every action before you do it: "I'm going to check your blood pressure now."</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <!-- connector -->
  <div class="phase-connector">⬇ As you perform your initial assessment, more information emerges…</div>

  <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       PHASE 2 — HISTORY & MEDICATION RECONCILIATION
  ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="phase2">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Phase 2</span>
      <h2>History &amp; Medication Reconciliation</h2>
    </div>

    <p class="phase-intro">
      Mrs. Jackson's daughter arrives and provides additional history. You also complete a thorough medication reconciliation.
    </p>

    <div class="info-grid">
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>🗣 History from Daughter</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Bernadette lives at home; normally alert and independent in ADLs</li>
          <li>Her primary care doctor started <strong>oxybutynin</strong> one week ago for urinary urgency and leakage</li>
          <li>She started taking <strong>loratadine (Claritin)</strong> over-the-counter 5 days ago for seasonal allergies — her doctor did not know</li>
          <li>Over the past 2–3 days she has been drinking less and seemed "off" — more confused than usual</li>
          <li>This morning she fell trying to get to the bathroom; daughter brought her to the ED</li>
          <li>Has a history of urinary incontinence and atrial fibrillation (on digoxin)</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>⚠️ Beers Criteria Flags</h3>
        <div class="callout callout-warning">
          <p>The <strong>AGS Beers Criteria</strong> identifies medications potentially inappropriate for adults ≥ 65 years. Two of Mrs. Jackson's medications raise immediate flags:</p>
          <table class="data-table" style="margin-top: 0.75rem;">
            <thead><tr><th>Medication</th><th>Beers Concern</th></tr></thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>Oxybutynin</strong></td>
                <td>⚠️ HIGH anticholinergic burden → urinary retention, confusion in elderly</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>Digoxin</strong></td>
                <td>⚠️ Narrow therapeutic window; toxicity risk rises with dehydration</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>Loratadine</strong> (2nd-gen)</td>
                <td>Mild anticholinergic — compounded oxybutynin's effects</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3>🔗 The Polypharmacy Chain — Connecting the Dots</h3>
    <div class="chain-flow">
      <div class="chain-step chain-step-drug">
        <span class="chain-icon">💊</span>
        <strong>Oxybutynin + Loratadine</strong>
        <small>Combined anticholinergic effects</small>
      </div>
      <div class="chain-arrow">↓</div>
      <div class="chain-step chain-step-problem">
        <span class="chain-icon">🚫</span>
        <strong>Urinary Retention</strong>
        <small>Bladder muscle relaxed; cannot empty fully</small>
      </div>
      <div class="chain-arrow">↓</div>
      <div class="chain-step chain-step-problem">
        <span class="chain-icon">🦠</span>
        <strong>Bacterial Growth → UTI</strong>
        <small>Stagnant urine = breeding ground for bacteria</small>
      </div>
      <div class="chain-arrow">↓</div>
      <div class="chain-step chain-step-consequence">
        <span class="chain-icon">🧠</span>
        <strong>Systemic Infection</strong>
        <small>Acute confusion · Fall risk · Dehydration</small>
      </div>
    </div>

    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Pre-Sim Q1: What are risk factors for developing a UTI in the elderly?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Female sex</strong> — shorter urethra, closer to rectum; post-menopausal urethral changes</li>
          <li><strong>Advanced age</strong> — weakened bladder muscle, decreased immune response</li>
          <li><strong>Urinary retention</strong> — allows bacteria to multiply in stagnant urine</li>
          <li><strong>Anticholinergic medications</strong> — oxybutynin and loratadine caused retention in Bernadette</li>
          <li><strong>Catheter use</strong> — disrupts normal urine flushing; allows organism migration</li>
          <li><strong>Dehydration</strong> — concentrated urine is more hospitable to bacteria</li>
          <li><strong>Incontinence</strong> — increases perineal skin exposure to bacteria</li>
          <li><strong>History of prior UTIs</strong> — increases recurrence susceptibility</li>
          <li><strong>Frequent healthcare facility exposure</strong> — increases exposure to resistant organisms</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Pre-Sim Q3: How do we prevent UTIs in the elderly population?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <ol>
          <li>Encourage adequate fluid intake — especially water, to flush bacteria</li>
          <li>Proper perineal hygiene — wipe front to back; hand hygiene before/after peri care</li>
          <li>Respond promptly to toileting needs — do not let the patient hold urine</li>
          <li>Avoid unnecessary catheters — remove as soon as clinically possible</li>
          <li><strong>Limit anticholinergic medications</strong> — apply Beers Criteria review</li>
          <li>Avoid bladder irritants — caffeine, alcohol, carbonated beverages</li>
          <li>Regular voiding schedule — every 2–3 hours during the day</li>
          <li>Thorough medication reconciliation at every care transition</li>
        </ol>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <!-- connector -->
  <div class="phase-connector">⬇ You begin your head-to-toe assessment…</div>

  <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       PHASE 3 — ASSESSMENT FINDINGS
  ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="phase3">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Phase 3</span>
      <h2>Assessment Findings</h2>
    </div>

    <p class="phase-intro">
      You perform a systematic head-to-toe assessment with a focused genitourinary component. Mrs. Jackson is restless and intermittently confused throughout.
    </p>

    <div class="info-grid">
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>🌡️ Vital Signs</h3>
        <table class="data-table">
          <tbody>
            <tr><th>Temperature</th><td>37.9°C (100.2°F) <span class="badge-warning">Low-grade</span></td></tr>
            <tr><th>Blood Pressure</th><td>102/68 mmHg <span class="badge-warning">Low-normal</span></td></tr>
            <tr><th>Heart Rate</th><td>96 bpm <span class="badge-warning">Mild tachycardia</span></td></tr>
            <tr><th>Respiratory Rate</th><td>20 breaths/min</td></tr>
            <tr><th>SpO₂</th><td>96% on room air</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Pain</th><td>4/10 lower abdominal discomfort</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>🧠 Neurological / Mental Status</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Alert but <strong>disoriented to place and time</strong></li>
          <li>Knows her name; does not know what hospital or what day it is</li>
          <li>Asking repeatedly for her daughter</li>
          <li>Restless — attempting to get out of bed without assistance</li>
          <li>Speech intact but somewhat tangential</li>
          <li><strong>This is NEW confusion</strong> — daughter confirms she was baseline alert at home</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="info-grid">
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>❤️ Cardiovascular</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Apical pulse regular at 96 bpm</li>
          <li>Peripheral pulses present and equal bilaterally</li>
          <li>No peripheral edema</li>
          <li><em>Note: Digoxin on board — apical pulse critical before administration</em></li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>🫁 Respiratory</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Lung sounds clear bilaterally</li>
          <li>RR 20 — at upper limit of normal</li>
          <li>No accessory muscle use</li>
          <li>SpO₂ 96% — adequate</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="info-grid">
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>🫃 Abdomen / GU Assessment</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Abdomen soft but <strong>suprapubic tenderness</strong> noted</li>
          <li>Mild distension present</li>
          <li>Bowel sounds present in all quadrants</li>
          <li>Bladder palpable above symphysis pubis → <strong>bladder distension confirmed</strong></li>
          <li>Urinary catheter placed by ED nurse → drainage bag shows <strong>small amount of dark, cloudy, foul-smelling urine</strong></li>
          <li>Perineal skin intact</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>🦴 Musculoskeletal / Skin</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Skin dry and warm; mucous membranes dry</li>
          <li>Skin turgor slightly decreased (tenting noted)</li>
          <li>No skin breakdown or pressure injuries</li>
          <li>Moves all extremities but weak bilaterally</li>
          <li>Reports feeling "too weak to stand alone"</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Clinical Reasoning: Why is Mrs. Jackson confused? Why is there NO high fever despite an infection?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>Why confusion instead of typical UTI symptoms?</strong></p>
        <p>
          In elderly patients, the classic UTI symptoms (burning, urgency, frequency) are often <em>absent</em>. Aging causes a blunted inflammatory response — the immune system does not mount the same reaction as in younger adults. Instead, systemic infection triggers neurotransmitter and cytokine changes that impair brain function, producing <strong>acute delirium</strong>. Confusion, lethargy, agitation, and falls are often the <em>only</em> presenting signs of UTI in older adults.
        </p>
        <p><strong>Why no high fever?</strong></p>
        <p>
          Elderly patients frequently do not mount a significant febrile response to infection — a baseline temperature may actually be lower in older adults. A temperature of 37.9°C that seems only mildly elevated may represent a significant infectious process in an 85-year-old. <strong>Do not rule out serious infection based on the absence of high fever in elderly patients.</strong>
        </p>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Pre-Sim Q2: What are the differences between upper and lower urinary tract infections?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <div class="compare-grid">
          <div>
            <h4>Lower UTI (Cystitis — bladder/urethra)</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Dysuria (painful or burning urination)</li>
              <li>Urinary frequency and urgency</li>
              <li>Cloudy or foul-smelling urine</li>
              <li>Hematuria</li>
              <li>Suprapubic discomfort or pressure</li>
              <li><strong>In elderly: classic symptoms may be absent — confusion, lethargy, or falls may be the only sign</strong></li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div>
            <h4>Upper UTI (Pyelonephritis — kidneys)</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Fever above 101°F (38.3°C)</li>
              <li>Chills and rigors</li>
              <li>Flank or lower back pain</li>
              <li>Nausea and vomiting</li>
              <li>All symptoms of lower UTI may also be present</li>
              <li><strong>More serious — can progress to urosepsis</strong></li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="callout callout-info" style="margin-top: 1rem;">
          <strong>Key point:</strong> Bernadette's confusion is an atypical sign of a lower UTI. Upper UTI must be ruled out. Monitor for flank pain, rigors, and worsening vital signs.
        </div>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Pre-Sim Q8: What assessment questions do you ask a patient with a suspected UTI?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <ul>
          <li>"Which problems are you having with passing urine?"</li>
          <li>"Do you feel like you are completely emptying your bladder?"</li>
          <li>"Does it hurt or burn when you urinate?"</li>
          <li>"How often are you urinating?"</li>
          <li>"Have you noticed any blood in your urine?"</li>
          <li>"Do you have any pain in your lower abdomen, back, or sides?"</li>
          <li>"Have you had a UTI before?"</li>
          <li>"What medications are you currently taking?" <em>(screen for anticholinergics)</em></li>
          <li>"How much fluid are you drinking each day?"</li>
          <li><em>For confused patients — direct questions to family/caregiver as needed</em></li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <!-- connector -->
  <div class="phase-connector">⬇ The laboratory and diagnostic results are ready…</div>

  <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       PHASE 4 — DIAGNOSTIC RESULTS
  ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="phase4">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Phase 4</span>
      <h2>Diagnostic Results Arrive</h2>
    </div>

    <p class="phase-intro">
      The ED sent a urinalysis and bladder scan before the catheter was placed. Results are now available in the chart.
    </p>

    <div class="info-grid">
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>🔬 Urinalysis Results</h3>
        <table class="data-table">
          <thead><tr><th>Finding</th><th>Result</th><th>Significance</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td>Specific gravity</td>
              <td><strong>1.030</strong> <span class="badge-warning">High</span></td>
              <td>Concentrated urine → dehydration</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Color / clarity</td>
              <td>Dark yellow, cloudy</td>
              <td>Abnormal — infection and dehydration</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Odor</td>
              <td>Foul / ammonia-like</td>
              <td>Consistent with bacterial infection</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Bacteria</td>
              <td><span class="badge-danger">Positive</span></td>
              <td>Confirms UTI</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>WBCs</td>
              <td><span class="badge-danger">Elevated</span></td>
              <td>Inflammatory response to infection</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Nitrites</td>
              <td><span class="badge-danger">Positive</span></td>
              <td>Gram-negative bacteria present</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>🏥 Bladder Scan &amp; Catheter</h3>
        <div class="stat-highlight">
          <span class="stat-number">620 mL</span>
          <span class="stat-label">drained by catheter on admission</span>
        </div>
        <p style="margin-top: 1rem;">
          Normal post-void residual is <strong>&lt; 50–100 mL</strong>. Bernadette had <strong>620 mL</strong> of retained urine — over 6× the acceptable limit. This stagnant urine created the ideal environment for bacterial growth.
        </p>
        <h3 style="margin-top: 1.25rem;">🧪 Pending Labs</h3>
        <table class="data-table">
          <tbody>
            <tr><th>CMP</th><td>Pending — monitor electrolytes and kidney function</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Digoxin level</th><td><span class="badge-danger">Pending — MUST check before next dose</span></td></tr>
            <tr><th>Urine culture &amp; sensitivity</th><td>Pending — sent before antibiotics started</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </div>

    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Post-Sim Q1: Specific gravity is 1.030. What does this indicate?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p>
          A specific gravity of 1.030 indicates <strong>concentrated urine</strong>, a sign of <strong>dehydration</strong>. The normal range is 1.005–1.030. At the upper end of or above normal range, the kidneys are retaining water because the body is volume-depleted.
        </p>
        <p>
          This is consistent with Bernadette's presentation — UTI, urinary retention, and inadequate fluid intake have all contributed to dehydration. Treatment with IV 0.9% Normal Saline directly addresses this by restoring circulating volume and promoting renal perfusion.
        </p>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Post-Sim Q2: Why is confusion the presenting symptom instead of burning or urgency?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p>
          Confusion in elderly patients is a classic — and often the <strong>only</strong> — presenting symptom of a UTI. Unlike younger adults who experience burning and urgency, older adults frequently present with sudden-onset confusion, agitation, lethargy, or falls <em>without</em> classic urinary symptoms.
        </p>
        <p>
          This is because aging-related changes in the immune system produce a blunted inflammatory response. The systemic infection causes changes in cytokines and neurotransmitters that impair brain function, leading to <strong>acute delirium superimposed on baseline cognition</strong>.
        </p>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Pre-Sim Q7: What are the common diagnostic tests of the urinary tract and nursing considerations?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <table class="data-table">
          <thead><tr><th>Test</th><th>Purpose</th><th>Nursing Considerations</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Urinalysis (UA)</strong></td>
              <td>Analyzes chemical and physical properties of urine</td>
              <td>Collect midstream clean-catch; send promptly; note color, clarity, odor</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Urine Culture &amp; Sensitivity</strong></td>
              <td>Identifies organism and effective antibiotics</td>
              <td>Use sterile technique; <strong>send before starting antibiotics if possible</strong></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Bladder Scan (Ultrasound)</strong></td>
              <td>Measures post-void residual urine volume</td>
              <td>Non-invasive; no radiation; patient may need a full bladder; do not schedule within 24 hr of IVP</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>CT Scan / IVP</strong></td>
              <td>Identifies structural abnormalities</td>
              <td>Check for contrast dye allergy; patient must lie still; encourage fluids after to flush dye</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Renal/Bladder Ultrasound</strong></td>
              <td>Identifies masses, obstruction, hydronephrosis, calculi</td>
              <td>Non-invasive; no radiation; verify preprocedural orders</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <!-- connector -->
  <div class="phase-connector">⬇ The full clinical picture is now visible — time to reason and act…</div>

  <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       PHASE 5 — CLINICAL REASONING: CONNECTING THE DOTS
  ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="phase5">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Phase 5</span>
      <h2>Clinical Reasoning — Connecting the Dots</h2>
    </div>

    <p class="phase-intro">
