    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Post-Sim Q6: What specific risk factors does Bernadette have for UTI? Explain how each contributed.</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Female sex</strong> — Women have shorter urethras (~4 cm) and the urethral meatus is closer to the rectum, making it easier for bacteria (especially E. coli) to enter the urinary tract.</li>
          <li><strong>Advanced age (85 years)</strong> — Aging causes bladder muscle weakness, decreased immune response, and reduced ability to completely empty the bladder.</li>
          <li><strong>Oxybutynin use</strong> — This anticholinergic medication relaxes bladder smooth muscle, causing urinary retention. Stagnant urine became a breeding ground for bacteria.</li>
          <li><strong>Loratadine (OTC)</strong> — Though milder, it also has anticholinergic properties that compounded oxybutynin's effect, worsening retention.</li>
          <li><strong>Urinary retention</strong> — The 620 mL confirms significant retention. The normal flushing action of voiding was lost, allowing bacteria to proliferate.</li>
          <li><strong>Catheter use</strong> — Once placed, a urinary catheter introduces a pathway for bacteria to migrate into the bladder, increasing CAUTI risk.</li>
        </ol>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Post-Sim Q7: Bernadette has mixed urinary incontinence. Which statement indicates accurate understanding?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>Mixed urinary incontinence</strong> combines both:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Stress incontinence</strong> — involuntary leakage during increased abdominal pressure (coughing, sneezing, lifting)</li>
          <li><strong>Urge incontinence</strong> — involuntary loss of urine after a sudden, strong urge to void</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          The correct understanding: <em>"The patient's incontinence results from involuntary leakage during periods of abdominal pressure AND the involuntary loss of urine after a strong urge to void."</em>
        </p>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Pre-Sim Q4: What other problems can occur if a UTI is not treated promptly?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Pyelonephritis</strong> — Bacteria ascend to the kidneys; causes high fever, chills, flank/back pain, nausea, vomiting; can cause permanent kidney damage</li>
          <li><strong>Urosepsis / Sepsis</strong> — Bacteria enter the bloodstream; life-threatening; signs include HR &gt; 90, RR &gt; 20, altered mental status, decreased urine output, hypotension</li>
          <li><strong>Chronic kidney disease</strong> — Repeated or untreated infections cause scarring and long-term impaired kidney function</li>
          <li><strong>Worsening delirium</strong> — In elderly patients, untreated infection deepens confusion, increases fall risk, and can lead to permanent cognitive decline</li>
        </ol>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

