    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Pre-Sim Q5: What is the plan of care for a confused patient with a UTI?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Ensure patient safety</strong> — lowest bed position, siderails up, call light within reach, non-slip socks, fall precautions sign</li>
          <li><strong>Reorient gently and frequently</strong> — use patient's name, explain location, explain every action</li>
          <li><strong>Administer ordered medications</strong> — Levofloxacin IV (antibiotic), Acetaminophen (comfort), Normal Saline IV (rehydration)</li>
          <li><strong>Encourage fluid intake</strong> — oral fluids if able to take them safely</li>
          <li><strong>Maintain catheter care</strong> — closed drainage, bag below bladder, assess site</li>
          <li><strong>Monitor urine output and characteristics</strong> — color, odor, clarity, amount</li>
          <li><strong>Involve family</strong> — they help with reorientation and communication</li>
          <li><strong>Monitor vital signs</strong> — watch for fever, tachycardia, hypotension (signs of worsening sepsis)</li>
          <li><strong>Document thoroughly</strong> in EHR / SimChart</li>
          <li><strong>Reassess regularly</strong> — evaluate response to treatment; watch for deterioration</li>
        </ol>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Post-Sim Q3 &amp; Q4: What catheter type is most appropriate and what are the indications for each type?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p>For <strong>short-term use</strong>, an <strong>intermittent (straight) catheter</strong> is preferred because it reduces CAUTI risk, allows normal voiding to resume between catheterizations, and minimizes bacterial colonization.</p>
        <p>However, because Bernadette has significant retention and requires continuous output monitoring, a short-term <strong>indwelling Foley catheter</strong> is appropriate initially — with the goal of early removal.</p>
        <table class="data-table" style="margin-top: 0.75rem;">
          <thead><tr><th>Type</th><th>Indications</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Intermittent/Straight</strong></td>
              <td>Urinary retention (drain once) · Sterile urine specimen · Prolonged immobilization · Bladder training</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Indwelling/Foley</strong></td>
              <td>Retention requiring continuous drainage · Surgery · Accurate output monitoring · Incontinence causing skin breakdown · Bladder outlet obstruction</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Suprapubic</strong></td>
              <td>Urethral trauma or obstruction · Post-urological surgery · Long-term retention when urethral catheterization not feasible</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Post-Sim Q5: What catheter care steps prevent worsening of Bernadette's infection?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Maintain a closed drainage system</strong> at all times — never disconnect tubing unnecessarily</li>
          <li><strong>Keep the drainage bag below bladder level</strong> — prevents backflow of urine</li>
          <li><strong>Do not allow tubing to kink or loop</strong> — ensures unobstructed urine flow</li>
          <li><strong>Perform perineal/catheter care</strong> with soap and water daily and after bowel movements — clean away from the meatus</li>
          <li><strong>Secure the catheter</strong> to the thigh to prevent tugging and urethral trauma</li>
          <li><strong>Empty the drainage bag regularly</strong> (when ²⁄₃ full) using a separate container; avoid the spigot touching the container</li>
          <li><strong>Monitor for signs of CAUTI</strong> — fever, new onset confusion, cloudy urine, pain at catheter site</li>
          <li><strong>Reassess daily</strong> for need of catheter — remove as soon as clinically possible</li>
        </ol>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Post-Sim Q8: What vital signs must be assessed before giving digoxin or a beta-blocker?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Blood pressure</strong> — hold if systolic BP &lt; 90 mmHg (or per facility policy)</li>
          <li><strong>Heart rate (apical pulse for 1 full minute)</strong> — hold digoxin if HR &lt; 60 bpm; hold beta-blocker if HR &lt; 60 bpm</li>
          <li><strong>Respiratory rate</strong> — hold beta-blocker if significantly abnormal</li>
          <li><strong>Digoxin level</strong> (when available) — therapeutic range 0.5–2.0 ng/mL; toxicity occurs above 2.0 ng/mL</li>
        </ol>
        <div class="callout callout-warning" style="margin-top: 0.75rem;">
          <strong>Clinical note:</strong> Dehydration increases the risk of digoxin toxicity. Bernadette's dehydration makes checking her digoxin level <em>especially critical</em> before administration.
        </div>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

