  <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       APPENDIX B — POLYPHARMACY & BEERS CRITERIA
  ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <div class="phase-card appendix-card" id="appendix-beers">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge phase-badge-appendix">Appendix B</span>
      <h2>Polypharmacy &amp; Beers Criteria</h2>
    </div>

    <div class="info-grid">
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>What is Polypharmacy?</h3>
        <p>The concurrent use of <strong>5 or more medications</strong>. Bernadette exemplifies polypharmacy — she takes digoxin, oxybutynin, loratadine, and other medications simultaneously.</p>
        <h4>Risk Factors</h4>
        <ul>
          <li>Multiple chronic conditions</li>
          <li>Multiple prescribers and pharmacies</li>
          <li>Use of OTC medications without provider knowledge</li>
          <li>Transitions of care (hospital to home)</li>
        </ul>
        <h4 style="margin-top: 0.75rem;">Problems Caused</h4>
        <ul>
          <li>Drug–drug interactions</li>
          <li>Increased fall risk</li>
          <li>Cognitive impairment</li>
          <li>Adverse drug events</li>
          <li>Higher risk of mortality</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>What is the Beers Criteria?</h3>
        <p>The <strong>American Geriatrics Society (AGS) Beers Criteria</strong> is a list of medications considered potentially inappropriate for adults ≥ 65 years due to increased risk of harm.</p>
        <table class="data-table" style="margin-top: 0.75rem;">
          <thead><tr><th>Medication</th><th>Why It's on the List</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td><strong>Oxybutynin</strong></td><td>High anticholinergic burden → confusion, urinary retention</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Digoxin</strong></td><td>Narrow therapeutic window; toxicity ↑ with dehydration or renal impairment</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>First-gen antihistamines</strong> (e.g., diphenhydramine)</td><td>High anticholinergic burden; loratadine (2nd-gen) has milder effects</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Benzodiazepines</strong></td><td>Increased fall risk, cognitive impairment</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>NSAIDs</strong></td><td>Increased GI bleeding, kidney injury risk</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
        <h4 style="margin-top: 0.75rem;">How Nurses Help</h4>
        <ul>
          <li>Thorough medication reconciliation at all care transitions</li>
          <li>Identify anticholinergic burden using Beers Criteria</li>
          <li>Assess patient understanding of all medications including OTC drugs</li>
          <li>Collaborate with the interdisciplinary team to deprescribe when appropriate</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       APPENDIX C — THERAPEUTIC COMMUNICATION REFERENCE
  ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <div class="phase-card appendix-card" id="appendix-comm">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge phase-badge-appendix">Appendix C</span>
      <h2>Therapeutic Communication — Quick Reference</h2>
    </div>

    <div class="compare-grid">
      <div>
        <h4 class="text-success">✓ Do</h4>
        <ul>
          <li>Use simple, short sentences</li>
          <li>Speak slowly and calmly</li>
          <li>Reorient gently: <em>"You are safe, you are in the hospital."</em></li>
          <li>Use her preferred name throughout</li>
          <li>Explain each action before doing it</li>
          <li>Make eye contact; approach from the front</li>
          <li>Involve family in communication and the care plan</li>
          <li>Ask one question at a time</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div>
        <h4 class="text-danger">✗ Don't</h4>
        <ul>
          <li>Use medical jargon or complex sentences</li>
          <li>Raise your voice or rush</li>
          <li>Argue with or correct the patient harshly</li>
          <li>Use terms like "honey" or "sweetie" without consent</li>
          <li>Perform procedures without warning</li>
          <li>Approach from behind unexpectedly</li>
          <li>Exclude family from the care plan</li>
          <li>Ask multiple questions simultaneously</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

